05934nam a22009015i 9783110730203DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20212021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2021937994  a97831107302037 a10.1515/97831107302032doi  a(DE-B1597)572955  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04aThe Apocalyptic Dimensions of Climate Change /ced. by Jan Alber. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (VIII, 182 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCulture & Conflict ;v1900tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tThe Apocalyptic Dimensions of Climate Change between the Disciplines -- tScenarios of Human-Induced Climate and Environmental Changes at Different Spatial and Temporal Scales -- tThe Apocalyptic Imagination and Climate Change -- tNarrative and the Texture of Catastrophe -- tHindu Apocalyptic Notions, Cultural Discourses, and Climate Change -- tThe Desert Wasteland and Climate Change in Mad Max: Fury Road -- tDrawing (on) the Future: Narration, Animation, and the Partially Human -- tEnvironmental Sciences, Apocalyptic Thought, and the Proxy of God -- tFour Cosmopolitical Ideas for an Unworlded World -- tClimate Change, the Apocalypse, and Other Ideologies in The Day after Tomorrow -- tBiographical Information -- tSubject Index -- tName Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aClimate change and the apocalypse are frequently associated in the popular imagination of the twenty-first century. This collection of essays brings together climatologists, theologians, historians, literary scholars, and philosophers to address and critically assess this association. The contributing authors are concerned, among other things, with the relation between cultural and scientific discourses on climate change; the role of apocalyptic images and narratives in representing environmental issues; and the tension between reality and fiction in apocalyptic representations of catastrophes. By focusing on how figures in fictional texts interact with their environment and deal with the consequences of climate change, this volume foregrounds the broader social and cultural function of apocalyptic narratives of climate change. By evoking a sense of collective human destiny in the face of the ultimate catastrophe, apocalyptic narratives have both cautionary and inspirational functions. Determining the extent to which such narratives square with scientific knowledge of climate change is one of the main aims of this book.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aClimate change.  aapocalypse.  acultural discourses.  anarrative.1 aAlber, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlber, Jan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCaracciolo, Marco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDimitrova, Diana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEckenhoff, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHegglund, Jon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJöris, Steffen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOegema, Gerbern S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRömer, Wolfgang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSegovia, Carlos A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSiegemund, Axel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTakvorian, Zoë, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook p